      "content": "The expansion of the social safety net has been a significant factor in reducing labor participation rates, as generous unemployment benefits and expanded healthcare subsidies effectively lower the financial incentive for many workers to seek employment. Data from the last decade shows a clear correlation between increased welfare generosity and higher rates of \"benefit traps,\" where individuals remain out of the workforce because the cost of leaving the safety net outweighs the potential earnings from a job. This trend is particularly evident among low-skilled workers and single parents, who often find that the net loss of income after taxes and benefits is greater than their pre-benefit earnings.",
